ming the ''[[:en:Bodaiji|Bodaiji]]'' of the Kuki clan. During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], the temple was supported by the [[Tokugawa shogunate]]. Its [[:en:Main Hall (Japanese Buddhism)|Hondō]] was built by [[:en:Ikeda Terumasa|Ikeda Terumasa]] in 1609, and was restored after a fire in 1701 by Keishōin, the mother of [[:en:Shogun|Shogun]] [[Tokugawa Tsunayoshi]]. It is designated a National Important Cultural Property.<ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=978-4311750403}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>
Following the [[Meiji Restoration|Meiji restoration]], the temple continued to draw pilgrims and tourists, especially after the construction of a cable car in 1925 to facilitate the steep climb up the mountain. However, the cable car was scrapped for metal during [[:en:Pacific War|Pacific War]], and visitors declined in numbers, especially after damage sustained in the [[:en:Typhoon Vera|Isewan Typhoon]] of 1959. This situation changed after the opening of the Iseshima Skyline highway in 1964.<ref name="Shiseki"/>
