{{nihongo| '''Kongōshō-ji'''|金剛證寺|}} is a {{ill|Rinzai school|en|Rinzai school|qid=Q639625|lt=Rinzai school|1=Rinzai school}} {{ill|Japanese Zen|en|Japanese Zen|qid=Q189424|lt=Zen|1=Japanese Zen}} {{ill|Buddhist temples in Japan|en|Buddhist temples in Japan|qid=Q3141900|lt=Buddhist temple|1=Buddhist temples in Japan}} in the Asamacho neighborhood of the city of {{ill|Ise, Mie|en|Ise, Mie|qid=Q328067|lt=Ise|1=Ise, Mie}}, {{ill|Mie Prefecture|en|Mie Prefecture|qid=Q128196|lt=Mie Prefecture|1=Mie Prefecture}} {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|qid=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}. Its [[honzon|main image]] is a statue of {{ill|Ākāśagarbha|en|Ākāśagarbha|qid=Q416174|lt=Kokūzō Bosatsu|1=Ākāśagarbha}}. Founded in the {{ill|Asuka period|en|Asuka period|qid=Q210688|lt=Asuka period|1=Asuka period}}, it has been closely associated with the [[Ise Grand Shrine]] throughout its history and contains numerous [[:en:National Treasure of Japan|National Treasures]] and {{ill|Important Cultural Property (Japan)|en|Important Cultural Property (Japan)|qid=Q1188622|lt=Important Cultural Properties|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}}. The {{ill|Sutra mound|en|Sutra mound|qid=Q7650105|lt=Sutra mound|1=Sutra mound}}s found on Mount Asama behind the temple were designated a [[:en:Historic Sites of Japan|National Historic Site]] in 1936.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/heritages/detail/210420|title=本居宣長墓（樹敬寺）附 本居春庭墓|language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=20 August 2020}}</ref>

==History==
The early history of Kongōshō-ji is uncertain. The temple claims that it was founded by {{ill|Emperor Kinmei|en|Emperor Kinmei|qid=Q329792|lt=Emperor Kinmei|1=Emperor Kinmei}}, who ordered the monk Kyōtai to build a chapel on this site in the middle of the 6th century. Later, {{ill|Kūkai|en|Kūkai|qid=Q222227|lt=Kūkai|1=Kūkai}} converted this chapel into a ''{{ill|Dojo|en|Dojo|qid=Q203609|lt=Dojo|1=Dojo}}'' for the teaching of {{ill|Shingon Buddhism|en|Shingon Buddhism|qid=Q550182|lt=Shingon|1=Shingon Buddhism}} esoteric Buddhism in 825 AD. As Kongōshō-ji is located to the northeast of the Ise Grand Shrine, it was regarded as the protector of the spiritually vulnerable northeastern direction from the shrine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iseshimaskyline.com/kongoushouji.htm |title=Kongōshō-ji |publisher=Mie Prefecture Tourism Development Company |accessdate=10 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122100632/http://www.iseshimaskyline.com/kongoushouji.htm |archive-date=22 January 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bes.or.jp/english/parks/iseshima.html |title=Ise-Shima National Park |publisher=National Parks Foundation |accessdate=11 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611210856/http://www.bes.or.jp/english/parks/iseshima.html |archive-date=11 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Furthermore, under the ''[[Shinbutsu-shūgō]]'' doctrines of medieval Japan, Kokūzō Bosatsu was regarded as an {{ill|Avatar|en|Avatar|qid=Q83090|lt=Avatar|1=Avatar}} of [[Amaterasu]], the principal ''[[kami]]'' of the Ise Grand Shrine, and thus the temple was regarded as an inner sanctum of that shrine. It attracted many pilgrims and grew to be the largest temple in {{ill|Ise Province|en|Ise Province|qid=Q864166|lt=Ise|1=Ise Province}} and {{ill|Shima Province|en|Shima Province|qid=Q1053722|lt=Shima Province|1=Shima Province}}s. The temple went into slow decline in the later {{ill|Heian period|en|Heian period|qid=Q193292|lt=Heian|1=Heian period}} and {{ill|Kamakura period|en|Kamakura period|qid=Q236205|lt=Kamakura period|1=Kamakura period}}s, until the priest Togaku Buniku of [[Kenchō-ji]] in {{ill|Kamakura|en|Kamakura|qid=Q200267|lt=Kamakura|1=Kamakura}} converted it into a Rinzai Zen temple in 1392. The temple was patronized by the naval commander {{ill|Kuki Yoshitaka|en|Kuki Yoshitaka|qid=Q921113|lt=Kuki Yoshitaka|1=Kuki Yoshitaka}} during the {{ill|Sengoku period|en|Sengoku period|qid=Q204023|lt=Sengoku period|1=Sengoku period}}, becoming the ''{{ill|Bodaiji|en|Bodaiji|qid=Q1084697|lt=Bodaiji|1=Bodaiji}}'' of the Kuki clan. During the {{ill|Edo period|en|Edo period|qid=Q184963|lt=Edo period|1=Edo period}}, the temple was supported by the [[Tokugawa shogunate]]. Its {{ill|Main Hall (Japanese Buddhism)|en|Main Hall (Japanese Buddhism)|qid=Q17051413|lt=Hondō|1=Main Hall (Japanese Buddhism)}} was built by {{ill|Ikeda Terumasa|en|Ikeda Terumasa|qid=Q1385927|lt=Ikeda Terumasa|1=Ikeda Terumasa}} in 1609, and was restored after a fire in 1701 by Keishōin, the mother of {{ill|Shogun|en|Shogun|qid=Q131767|lt=Shogun|1=Shogun}} [[Tokugawa Tsunayoshi]]. It is designated a National Important Cultural Property.<ref name="Shiseki">{{cite book |last1=Isomura |first1=Yukio |last2=Sakai |first2=Hideya |title=(国指定史跡事典) National Historic Site Encyclopedia |date=2012 |publisher=学生社 |isbn=978-4311750403}}{{in lang|ja}}</ref>

Following the [[Meiji Restoration|Meiji restoration]], the temple continued to draw pilgrims and tourists, especially after the construction of a cable car in 1925 to facilitate the steep climb up the mountain. However, the cable car was scrapped for metal during {{ill|Pacific War|en|Pacific War|qid=Q184425|lt=Pacific War|1=Pacific War}}, and visitors declined in numbers, especially after damage sustained in the {{ill|Typhoon Vera|en|Typhoon Vera|qid=Q1060156|lt=Isewan Typhoon|1=Typhoon Vera}} of 1959. This situation changed after the opening of the Iseshima Skyline highway in 1964.<ref name="Shiseki"/>

